{"entity": "IFSCA", "type": "organization", "description": "Indian Financial Services Centres Authority (IFSCA)  \nThe Indian Financial Services Centres Authority is a regulatory body established by the Indian government to oversee all financial activities conducted at Indian Financial Services Centres (IFSCs). It issues laws, rules, guidelines, circulars and other frameworks governing finance companies and finance units incorporated within India, and administers the registration process ensuring statutory compliance prior to service provision. In March 2022, IFSCA launched the FinTech Incentive Scheme, evaluating and approving grant applications to promote fintech innovation. The Authority also regulates the FinTech Regulatory Sandbox, providing Limited Use Authorisations for sandbox testing, and authorises FinTech entities that operate within IFSCs. It issues fee circulars and notices that dictate conduct and compliance obligations of participants in IFSCs.\n\nInternational Financial Services Centres Authority (IFSCA)  \nThe International Financial Services Centres Authority is a jurisdictional regulator that governs financial services beyond India’s borders, focusing on the global distribution of capital market and insurance products. Its mandate includes formulating and enforcing regulations for market‑making activities, the distribution of capital market products, and the provision of insurance services. The Authority issues specific fee circulars and regulatory notifications applicable to entities operating within its international framework and manages sandbox frameworks and the authorisation process for fintech activities in the international context.<SEP>The Indian FinTech Services Council, an organization that oversees grant processes and regulatory compliance.<SEP>IFSCA is the Indian Financial System Custodian Agency, the regulatory body receiving the applicant's submission.<SEP>The IFSCA is a regulatory body responsible for issuing regulations and frameworks governing technology and financial services in India."}
{"entity": "Financial Information", "type": "content", "description": "Financial data submitted by FinTech entities to IFSCA."}
{"entity": "Applicant", "type": "person", "description": "Applicant\n\nThe term Applicant refers to any entity—whether a corporate body, a startup, an individual, or a body corporate incorporated outside India—that submits a formal request to the International Financial Services Centres Authority (IFSCA) to obtain regulatory approval or participation under its FinTech framework. Applicants may pursue various pathways, including applying for direct authorization to conduct FinTech activities, seeking participation in the regulatory sandbox for limited use authorisation, or applying for grants under the FinTech Incentive Scheme. In each case, the Applicant must satisfy eligibility criteria set by IFSCA, such as demonstrating the nature of the proposed FinTech solution, compliance with statutory requirements, and possession of necessary supporting documents. When applying under the directive to authorise FinTech entities, the Applicant often needs to incorporate a corporate entity within the Indian Financial Technology and Services Centre (IFSC) and submit detailed documentation covering corporate structure, business model, technology roadmap, risk management, and compliance frameworks. For sandbox participation, Applicants must provide comprehensive documentation of their proposed solution, including technical specifications, operational plans, and risk mitigation measures. Throughout the application process, the Applicant must adhere to IFSCA guidelines governing licensing, supervision, and ongoing compliance, ensuring transparent communication and thorough evidence submission.<SEP>The Applicant is the unit applying to establish as an ancillary service provider in the IFSC, providing details such as name, address, legal form, contact, incorporation date, and shareholding pattern.<SEP>Applicant is the organization applying for the IFSCA grant.<SEP>Applicant is a company or limited liability partnership entity submitting an application to the IFSCA.<SEP>Applicant is the individual or entity seeking registration and submitting applications to the Authority."}
