{"entity": "International Financial Services Centres Authority", "type": "organization", "description": "International Financial Services Centres Authority (IFSCA) is a statutory authority established in 2020 to regulate all financial products, services, and institutions operating within India’s International Financial Services Centres (IFSCs). As the chief regulatory agency for these specialized financial hubs, IFSCA formulates and issues comprehensive guidelines and circulars that shape the operational framework of the IFSCs, ensuring services are delivered in compliance with national and international standards.\n\nIFSCA’s mandate extends across the full spectrum of IFSC activities. It oversees the FinTech sector by administering the FinTech Incentive Scheme, authorising FinTech entities, and conducting regulatory assessments under a licensing regime that grants approvals to FinTech solutions. This framework fosters innovation while safeguarding market integrity and the overall health of the financial ecosystem. In addition to FinTech, the authority manages a range of ancillary services—providing guidance, issuing approvals, and continually updating its regulatory regime to reflect evolving industry practices. It also oversees accelerators and other technology‑finance initiatives, issuing authorisations, fee assessments under the FE Framework, and grant schemes designed to stimulate growth within the IFSCs.\n\nBeyond regulatory oversight, IFSCA plays a pivotal role in developing the IFSC environment. It facilitates seamless collaboration between financial and non‑financial service providers, thereby supporting a robust, globally competitive financial ecosystem. Through its comprehensive guideline sets, incentive programmes, and continual regulatory evolution, IFSCA ensures that India’s International Financial Services Centres remain attractive and compliant international platforms for a wide range of financial and ancillary activities.<SEP>International Financial Services Centres Authority is the regulatory body that introduced the FinTech Incentive Scheme 2022 to promote FinTech hubs.<SEP>The International Financial Services Centres Authority (IFSCA) regulates and develops financial products and services in the International Financial Services Centre.<SEP>The IFSCA Authority issues circulars and regulates financial services in IFSCs under the IFSCA Act.<SEP>International Financial Services Centres Authority is the regulatory body overseeing activities within the IFSC and authorizes registration certificates for eligible entities.<SEP>The International Financial Services Centres Authority is a regulatory body established under the International Financial Services Centres Authority Act, 2019 to oversee and regulate financial services in India.<SEP>Regulatory body overseeing trusteeship and other services within International Financial Services Centres."}
